For this reason and overshadowing negative social stigma, it is not uncommon for women in the Islamic community to happily remain single and instead raise their child or children. Secondly, Ideologically, the separation of women and men is shared in belief among both Albanian and Muslim communities. For Muslim women, without marriage there are no legal or societal restrictions placed on their activities and mobility. Muslim women enjoy the freedoms associated with unmarried women, including their right to enter a work place of their choosing rather than being subject to restrictive marriage laws.[75]

There are also numerous feminist movements in Albania that have begun to carve out spaces for political activism. While most feminists are often associated with radical practices, these intellectuals have focused on different issues. For example Dr. Violeta Topall who after the war was one of the most powerful feminist agendas.[76]Topalli's group has demanded equal pay and equal pay for time with the child. This group has participated in the campaign for legal equality of which the final steps of were finally actes upon in 1995 giving women more control over society. After the research gained from this group, they found that a real danger persisted in the school seats of female Albanian youth and furthermore in the teachers.[77] The group and its goals encouraged female participants to join.
